<p>I drafted a post on how the <a href="https://dirtywave.com/">Dirtywave M8</a> is an amazing synth, but given the time and the growing scope of that post, I‚Äôll sum it up in a short blurb instead. For a single man project, this synth is a miracle. Very geeky, all shortcut driven, standing on the shoulders of tracker giants, particularly <a href="https://www.littlesounddj.com/lsd/index.php">LSDJ</a>, it has a solid workflow and most definitely isn‚Äôt a gimmick. You‚Äôll have to do without any visual aid. This is what I love on the Elektron boxes, where the display really helps you understand what you‚Äôre doing when filtering or creating an LFO. All you have here are hex numbers and consistent shortcuts. But it sounds absolutely marvelous and allows you to create music <em>anywhere</em>.</p>

<p>I‚Äôd like to share two tracks I‚Äôve learned the ropes of the device on, but also the genre itself. I‚Äôve listened to DNB mainly through <a href="https://soundcloud.com/visionrecordings">Noisia/Vision radio podcast</a> that made my runs possible (I hated running all my life, but it‚Äôs really the best way to combat the negative effects of sitting behind a computer all day). But I‚Äôve never actually tried producing a track within that DNB realm.</p>

